16	  - .stitch/screens.json
17	---
18	
19	# Breakdown UX to Screens
20	
21	Invoke **/ux-breakdown** skill to extract structured screen definitions from the UX overview.
22	
23	## Purpose
24	
25	This task transforms the high-level UX.md into machine-readable artifacts that downstream tasks can consume. It serves as the bridge between user experience design and implementation.
26	
27	## What Gets Generated
28	
29	### 1. `.stitch/SITE.md`
30	A human-readable sitemap showing:
31	- Navigation hierarchy
32	- All routes and their purposes
33	- User flow diagrams
34	- Screen relationships
35	
36	### 2. `.stitch/screens.json`
37	Machine-readable screen metadata. Contains **both** regular screens and overlay entries.
38	
39	**Regular screen entry fields:**
40	- `id` — Unique kebab-case identifier
41	- `title` — Human-readable name
42	- `route` — GoRouter path (e.g., `/novel/:id`)
43	- `description` — What the screen does
44	- `features` — Key features list
45	- `priority` — Implementation priority (1 = highest)
46	
47	**Overlay entry fields** (for bottom sheets, dialogs, persistent bars):
48	- `id` — Unique kebab-case identifier
49	- `title` — Human-readable name
50	- `route` — MUST use `overlay:` prefix (e.g., `overlay:mode-selector`)
51	- `description` — What the overlay does
52	- `parentScreenId` — ID of the screen that triggers this overlay
53	- `overlayType` — One of: `bottom-sheet`, `dialog`, `persistent-bar`
54	- `features` — Key features list
55	- `priority` — Implementation priority
56	
57	Example overlay entry:
58	```json
59	{
60	  "id": "settings-editor",
61	  "title": "Settings Editor",
62	  "route": "overlay:settings-editor",
63	  "description": "Bottom sheet for editing user preferences",
64	  "parentScreenId": "settings",
65	  "overlayType": "bottom-sheet",
66	  "features": ["form-fields", "save-button"],
67	  "priority": 1
68	}
69	```
70	
71	## Flutter-Specific Notes
72	
73	- Routes use GoRouter path format: `/path/:param`
74	- Bottom navigation screens use top-level routes: `/`, `/browse`, `/library`, `/profile`
75	- Detail screens use nested routes: `/novel/:id`, `/novel/:id/chapter/:chapterId`
76	- Overlay screens use `overlay:` prefix: `overlay:audio-player`
77	
78	## Extracting Overlays
79	
80	You MUST extract overlay entries from UX.md. Look for:
81	- Bottom sheets (selection pickers, entry forms, detail views)
82	- Dialogs (confirmations, alerts, settings)
83	- Persistent bars (audio players, media controls)
84	
85	Each overlay mentioned or implied in UX.md gets its own entry in `screens.json` with the `overlay:` route prefix, `parentScreenId`, and `overlayType`.
86	
87	## Success Criteria
88	
89	After completion:
90	- `.stitch/SITE.md` exists with clear navigation structure
91	- `.stitch/screens.json` exists with valid JSON schema
92	- All screens from UX.md are represented
93	- All overlays (bottom sheets, dialogs) from UX.md are represented with `overlay:` routes
94	- Screen IDs are unique and follow kebab-case convention
95	- Each screen has required fields (id, title, route, description)
96	- Each overlay has required fields (id, title, route, description, parentScreenId, overlayType)
97	
